Although alcohol sales in the United States have increased during the coronavirus pandemic, other countries are taking aggressive cautionary measures to prevent the spread of COVID-19.
Thailand’s capital, Bangkok, is banning alcohol sales for a week and a half to stop social gatherings that could spread the coronavirus, according to TIME.
Their reasoning is to reduce violence against children during a period of confinement due to the coronavirus, according to The Guardian.
In the City of Gallup, New Mexico alcohol is banned from convenience stores, but not grocery stores, according to KRQE.
About a month ago, Pennsylvania closed all its state-owned liquor stores in order to stop the spread of the coronavirus, however, the state reopened it’s state-own liquor stores online a few weeks ago.